\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
New ideas in parallel Particle Swarm Optimization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Vasileios Charilogis, Ioannis G.
 Tsoulos
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
Department of Informatics and Telecommunications, University of Ioannina
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
In global optimization there are techniques where they find the optimal
 solutions of the objective problems but waste a lot of computational time.
 The PSO parallelization technique proposed in this article significantly
 reduces the computation time and at the same time participates in the solution
 finding algorithm with the iterative communication between the parallel
 computing units.
 In addition, a new and more appropriate termination rule is proposed here.
 From the results of the experiments it appears that the overall parallelization
 technique is more than an accelerator of the classical algorithm.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph*
Keywords:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Optimization, Parallel methods, Evolutionary techniques, Stochastic methods,
 Termination rules
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The global optimization problem is usually defined as: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{*}=\mbox{arg}\min_{x\in S}f(x)\label{eq:eq1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\left[a_{1},b_{1}\right]\otimes\left[a_{2},b_{2}\right]\otimes\ldots\left[a_{n},b_{n}\right]
\]

\end_inset

where the function f is assumed to be continuous and differentiable.
 Many problems faced by researchers can be formulated as global minimization
 problems such as problems in physical science 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "go_physics1,go_physics2,go_physics3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, chemistry 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "go_chem1,go_chem2,go_chem3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, economics 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "go_econ1,go_econ2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and medicine 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "go_med1,go_med2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Τhe optimization method consists of two major categories: deterministic
 and stochastic methods.
 In the deterministic category, the most common category is the so - called
 interval methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "interval1,interval2"
literal "true"

\end_inset

, where the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is iteratively divided into subregions and those that do not contain a
 global solution, are discarded using certain criteria.
 In the case of the stochastic method, the finding of the global minimum
 is based on randomness operations, while there is no guarantee of finding
 the global minimum.
 Nevertheless, it is the method that is often used due to the simplicity
 of their application.
 Several researchers have proposed stochastic methods such as: controlled
 random search methods
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "crs1,crs2,crs3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, simulated annealing methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "simann_major,simann1,simann2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, differential evolution methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "diffe1,diffe2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, particle swarm optimization methods 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "pso_major,pso1,pso2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Ant Colony Optimization 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "aco1,aco2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, Genetic Algorithms [26, 27, 28], etc.
 Ιn conclusion, many studies have used the modern GPU processing units 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "gpu1,gpu2,gpu3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Some research that one can study regarding metaheuristic algorithms is
 presented in some recent papers 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "meta1,meta2,meta3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

